{
  "What is the maximum sustainable yield (MSY) of a fishery?": "",
  "The largest catch that can be taken from a fish stock year after year without depleting it": "",
  "The amount of fish a single boat can catch in one trip": "",
  "The minimum number of fish needed for a species to survive": "",
  "The total number of fish in the ocean": "",
  "Maximum sustainable yield is the theoretical largest harvest that can be taken from a fish population indefinitely without causing the population to decline, occurring when the population is at approximately half its carrying capacity.": "",
  "What is the primary cause of declining global fish stocks?": "",
  "Overfishing beyond sustainable levels": "",
  "Natural population fluctuations": "",
  "Increased predation by marine mammals": "",
  "Fish voluntarily leaving the ocean": "",
  "Overfishing, defined as harvesting fish faster than they can reproduce, is the primary cause of declining fish stocks worldwide; approximately one-third of global fish stocks are overfished according to the FAO.": "",
  "What is bycatch?": "",
  "Non-target species unintentionally caught during fishing operations": "",
  "A secondary fishing technique used after the primary catch": "",
  "Fish caught specifically for scientific research": "",
  "Fish that are caught and sold at market": "",
  "Bycatch refers to non-target marine organisms, including sea turtles, dolphins, sharks, and juvenile fish, that are unintentionally captured during commercial fishing operations and are often discarded dead or dying.": "",
  "What fishing method involves dragging a large weighted net along the ocean floor?": "",
  "Longlining": "",
  "Rod and reel fishing": "",
  "Bottom trawling": "",
  "Purse seining": "",
  "Bottom trawling involves dragging a heavy net along the seafloor to catch bottom-dwelling species; it is highly destructive to benthic habitats, including coral reefs and seagrass beds, and produces significant bycatch.": "",
  "What is the primary purpose of establishing marine protected areas (MPAs)?": "",
  "To extract oil and gas from the ocean floor": "",
  "To increase commercial fishing opportunities": "",
  "To create new islands for human habitation": "",
  "To conserve marine ecosystems and allow depleted populations to recover": "",
  "Marine protected areas restrict human activities like fishing and extraction in designated ocean zones, allowing marine ecosystems and depleted fish populations to recover, and serving as nurseries that can replenish fish stocks in surrounding areas.": "",
  "How does ocean acidification affect marine organisms?": "",
  "It increases the size of coral reefs": "",
  "It has no effect on marine organisms": "",
  "It makes the ocean more suitable for all marine life": "",
  "It reduces the ability of organisms to build calcium carbonate shells and skeletons": "",
  "Ocean acidification, caused by absorption of excess atmospheric CO2, lowers ocean pH and reduces carbonate ion availability, making it harder for organisms like corals, mollusks, and plankton to build and maintain their calcium carbonate shells and structures.": "",
  "What is coral bleaching?": "",
  "The expulsion of symbiotic algae from coral due to stress, causing corals to turn white": "",
  "A cleaning process that makes coral healthier": "",
  "The natural death of old coral colonies": "",
  "The natural color change of coral during reproduction": "",
  "Coral bleaching occurs when stressed corals expel the symbiotic zooxanthellae algae that live in their tissues and provide them with energy through photosynthesis; without these algae, the coral turns white and can die if the stress is prolonged.": "",
  "What is the tragedy of the commons as it relates to ocean fisheries?": "",
  "The depletion of shared resources because individuals act in self-interest rather than for the common good": "",
  "A government policy that distributes fish equally among citizens": "",
  "A fishing technique that catches only common species": "",
  "The natural decline of fish populations due to predation": "",
  "The tragedy of the commons describes how open-access resources like ocean fisheries become overexploited when each individual fisher maximizes their own catch without considering the cumulative effect on the shared resource, leading to stock collapse.": "",
  "Which international agreement regulates commercial whaling?": "",
  "The Montreal Protocol": "",
  "The Paris Agreement": "",
  "The International Whaling Commission (IWC) moratorium": "",
  "The Kyoto Protocol": "",
  "The International Whaling Commission implemented a moratorium on commercial whaling in 1986 to allow whale populations to recover from centuries of overexploitation, though some nations continue whaling under scientific research or cultural exemptions.": "",
  "What environmental problem is caused by ghost fishing?": "",
  "Abandoned or lost fishing gear continues to trap and kill marine organisms": "",
  "Fish populations increase to unsustainable levels": "",
  "Fish become invisible to predators": "",
  "Fishing boats operate without proper lighting": "",
  "Ghost fishing occurs when discarded, lost, or abandoned fishing nets and gear continue to entangle and kill marine animals for years, contributing to marine debris and causing significant unnecessary mortality of fish, turtles, and marine mammals.": "",
  "What does 'overfishing' mean?": "",
  "Catching only the largest fish in a population": "",
  "Harvesting fish at a rate faster than the population can reproduce and replenish itself": "",
  "Fishing in areas that are too deep for most boats": "",
  "Catching more fish than a boat can carry": "",
  "Overfishing occurs when fish are harvested at a rate that exceeds the population's ability to replace itself through reproduction, causing the stock to decline over time and potentially leading to population collapse.": "",
  "What does 'fishery collapse' mean?": "",
  "A temporary decrease in fish catches due to seasonal migration": "",
  "The dramatic decline of a fish population to less than 10% of its historical size, rendering it commercially unviable": "",
  "The closing of a fish market due to low demand": "",
  "A fish population reaching its carrying capacity": "",
  "Fishery collapse occurs when a fish stock declines to a critically low level (typically below 10% of its unfished biomass), making commercial fishing economically unviable and potentially threatening the population with ecological extinction.": "",
  "What does 'trawling' refer to?": "",
  "A fishing method that drags a large net through the water or along the ocean floor to catch fish": "",
  "Setting traps on the shore to catch fish at low tide": "",
  "Using sound waves to locate fish schools": "",
  "Fishing with a single line and hook": "",
  "Trawling is an industrial fishing method that involves pulling a large net (trawl) through the water column or along the seafloor behind a boat; it is highly efficient but can be destructive to habitats and produces significant bycatch.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'fishing down the food web'?": "",
  "Feeding fish in aquaculture facilities": "",
  "Catching fish that live at the bottom of the ocean": "",
  "The progressive shift to harvesting smaller, lower trophic level species after depleting larger predatory fish": "",
  "A method of fishing that releases all small fish": "",
  "Fishing down the food web describes the global trend of initially targeting large, high-trophic-level predatory fish and, as those stocks decline, progressively shifting to smaller, lower-trophic-level species, indicating cascading overexploitation of marine food webs.": "",
  "What does 'ocean acidification' mean?": "",
  "The decrease in ocean pH caused by absorption of excess atmospheric carbon dioxide": "",
  "The increase in ocean temperature due to global warming": "",
  "The addition of acid waste from factories into the ocean": "",
  "The natural pH fluctuations in tide pools": "",
  "Ocean acidification is the ongoing decrease in ocean pH caused by the absorption of excess atmospheric CO2; the ocean absorbs about 25-30% of human CO2 emissions, which reacts with seawater to form carbonic acid, lowering pH.": "",
  "What is meant by 'Individual Transferable Quota (ITQ)'?": "",
  "A fisheries management system that allocates a specific share of the total allowable catch to each fisher, which can be bought or sold": "",
  "A tax on fishing equipment": "",
  "A type of fishing net designed to catch individual fish": "",
  "A requirement for individual fishers to report their daily location": "",
  "ITQs are a market-based fisheries management tool that assigns each fisher a tradeable share of the total allowable catch, giving fishers a stake in the long-term health of the fishery and reducing the race to fish.": "",
  "What is 'upwelling' in the ocean?": "",
  "The rising of cold, nutrient-rich deep water to the ocean surface": "",
  "The horizontal movement of water along the coast": "",
  "The wave action caused by storms": "",
  "The sinking of warm surface water to the ocean depths": "",
  "Upwelling is the process by which wind-driven currents bring cold, nutrient-rich water from the deep ocean to the surface, fueling phytoplankton growth and creating some of the world's most productive fishing grounds.": "",
  "What does 'catch per unit effort (CPUE)' indicate?": "",
  "The number of fish species present in an area": "",
  "The amount of fish caught relative to the amount of fishing effort expended, used as an indicator of fish stock abundance": "",
  "The total cost of running a fishing operation": "",
  "The caloric content of different fish species": "",
  "CPUE measures the quantity of fish caught per unit of fishing effort (such as per hour of trawling or per hook set) and serves as an index of fish abundance; a declining CPUE indicates that fish stocks are decreasing.": "",
  "What does 'marine biodiversity' refer to?": "",
  "The variety of life forms found in ocean and coastal ecosystems, including genetic, species, and ecosystem diversity": "",
  "The diversity of ships and boats used for fishing": "",
  "Only the number of fish species in the ocean": "",
  "The total biomass of all organisms in the ocean": "",
  "Marine biodiversity encompasses the full range of biological variation in ocean and coastal environments at all levels, from genetic diversity within species to species diversity within ecosystems to the diversity of marine habitat types.": "",
  "What is 'sustainable fishing'?": "",
  "Harvesting fish at a rate that allows populations to maintain themselves over time without degrading the ecosystem": "",
  "Catching as many fish as possible in the shortest time": "",
  "Fishing only in freshwater lakes": "",
  "Using only traditional fishing methods from past centuries": "",
  "Sustainable fishing means catching fish at a rate that does not exceed the population's capacity to replenish itself, using methods that minimize habitat damage and bycatch, ensuring healthy fish stocks for current and future generations.": "",
  "The Atlantic cod fishery off Newfoundland, Canada, was one of the world's most productive for 500 years. In 1992, the Canadian government imposed a moratorium on cod fishing after the stock collapsed to less than 1% of historical levels. Despite the ban, cod populations have still not fully recovered after 30 years. What factors likely prevent recovery?": "",
  "Ecological changes including altered food webs, increased predation on juvenile cod, and changed ocean conditions make recovery difficult": "",
  "Cod have migrated permanently to warmer waters within the broader context of populations analysis": "",
  "The moratorium caused too many cod to survive, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The moratorium was lifted too soon according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "After severe depletion, fish populations may not recover quickly because the ecosystem has shifted: species that compete with or prey on cod have filled the ecological void, environmental conditions have changed, and the reduced population may have insufficient genetic diversity or reproductive capacity.": "",
  "A Pacific island nation that depends heavily on tuna fishing notices that their catches have declined significantly. Scientists determine that large foreign industrial fishing fleets are operating just outside the nation's exclusive economic zone. What international management approach would best protect this nation's fisheries?": "",
  "Each country should fish as much as it wants in international waters": "",
  "Regional fisheries management organizations should set science-based catch limits for the entire tuna stock across all fishing nations": "",
  "Tuna should be listed as an endangered species and all fishing banned": "",
  "The island nation should stop fishing entirely": "",
  "Since tuna migrate across national boundaries and into international waters, effective management requires cooperative regional or international agreements that set total allowable catches based on scientific stock assessments and distribute quotas equitably among fishing nations.": "",
  "A marine biologist studies a coral reef where large herbivorous fish have been heavily fished. She observes that algae are overgrowing and smothering the coral. What trophic interaction explains why removing herbivorous fish leads to coral decline?": "",
  "Herbivorous fish produce chemicals that protect coral from algae": "",
  "Without herbivorous fish to control algae growth, algae outcompete coral for space and light on the reef": "",
  "Algae growth is unrelated to fish populations": "",
  "Herbivorous fish eat coral, and their removal allows coral to grow unchecked": "",
  "Herbivorous fish like parrotfish and surgeonfish play a critical role in maintaining coral reef health by grazing on algae; when these fish are removed by overfishing, algae proliferate and smother coral, leading to a phase shift from coral-dominated to algae-dominated reefs.": "",
  "Aquaculture now produces more fish for human consumption than wild capture fisheries. However, a major environmental concern is that salmon farms in coastal waters have led to disease outbreaks that affect wild salmon populations. What mechanism allows farmed fish diseases to spread to wild populations?": "",
  "Aquaculture facilities are always located far from wild fish habitat": "",
  "Farmed fish are immune to all diseases": "",
  "Wild fish never come near aquaculture facilities": "",
  "High densities of farmed fish create pathogen breeding grounds, and sea lice and viruses spread through open water to wild fish swimming nearby": "",
  "Open-net salmon farms concentrate thousands of fish in small areas, creating ideal conditions for parasites like sea lice and viral diseases to multiply; pathogens and parasites spread through the water to wild salmon, especially juveniles migrating past farms.": "",
  "The Great Barrier Reef has experienced multiple mass bleaching events in recent years, with the 2016-2017 events killing approximately 50% of the reef's coral. Scientists link these events to marine heat waves caused by climate change. Why are repeated bleaching events more damaging than single events?": "",
  "Repeated bleaching events have no additional impact beyond the first": "",
  "Bleaching events only affect dead coral": "",
  "Corals need years to recover between bleaching events; repeated events prevent recovery and kill already-weakened coral": "",
  "Coral becomes stronger with each bleaching event": "",
  "Coral recovery from bleaching typically requires 10-15 years of favorable conditions; when bleaching events occur more frequently than this recovery period, corals that survived the first event have not regained their energy reserves and algal symbionts, making subsequent bleaching more lethal.": "",
  "A fishing community in West Africa has relied on artisanal fishing for generations. In recent years, catches have plummeted because large industrial trawlers from distant nations fish heavily in their coastal waters, often illegally. What is this type of fishing called, and why is it harmful?": "",
  "Recreational fishing; it has no impact on fish populations": "",
  "Illegal, unreported, and unregulated (IUU) fishing; it depletes fish stocks and threatens the food security and livelihoods of local communities": "",
  "Subsistence fishing; it is always beneficial to local communities": "",
  "Sustainable fishing; it helps both local and foreign fishers": "",
  "IUU fishing is a global problem where vessels fish illegally in other nations' waters or in violation of regulations, depleting fish stocks that local communities depend on for food and income; developing nations are disproportionately affected because they lack enforcement capacity.": "",
  "Ocean plastic pollution has been found in virtually every marine ecosystem, from surface waters to the deepest ocean trenches. Researchers find that many fish species have ingested microplastics. What is the concern about microplastics entering marine food webs?": "",
  "Microplastics can absorb and concentrate toxins, which bioaccumulate up the food chain and may ultimately affect human health": "",
  "Microplastics provide essential nutrients to marine organisms": "",
  "Microplastics have no effect on marine organisms or food webs": "",
  "Fish prefer to eat microplastics rather than natural food": "",
  "Microplastics absorb persistent organic pollutants from seawater; when ingested by marine organisms, these toxins can leach into tissues, and as contaminated prey are consumed by predators, pollutant concentrations increase at each trophic level, potentially affecting human seafood consumers.": "",
  "A marine biologist compares two adjacent reef systems: one within a well-enforced no-take marine protected area (MPA) and one open to fishing. The MPA reef has 4 times more fish biomass, larger individual fish, and greater coral cover. Fishers outside the MPA also report better catches near the MPA boundaries. What explains the benefit to fishers outside the MPA?": "",
  "The MPA depletes fish from surrounding waters": "",
  "The MPA has no effect on areas outside its boundaries": "",
  "Fish from outside the MPA are attracted to the boundary by noise": "",
  "The spillover effect: adult fish and larvae from the protected, healthy population inside the MPA move into adjacent fishing areas": "",
  "The spillover effect occurs when the thriving fish population inside an MPA grows beyond the reserve's carrying capacity, and adult fish emigrate and larvae disperse into adjacent fishing grounds, effectively supplementing fish stocks and improving catches for fishers near the MPA.": "",
  "Scientists studying the decline of sea otter populations along the Pacific coast found that kelp forests disappeared after otter populations crashed, and the coastline experienced increased erosion. What does this cascade of effects illustrate about sea otters' role in the ecosystem?": "",
  "Sea otters are a keystone species whose removal triggers a trophic cascade: without otters to eat sea urchins, urchins overgraze kelp forests": "",
  "Sea otters are unimportant to marine ecosystems": "",
  "Sea otters cause kelp destruction through their feeding habits": "",
  "Kelp forests disappear naturally regardless of otter populations": "",
  "Sea otters are a keystone species that controls sea urchin populations; without otters, urchin populations explode and overgraze kelp forests, transforming productive kelp ecosystems into barren urchin barrens, demonstrating a classic trophic cascade from predator removal.": "",
  "A developing coastal nation plans to expand its aquaculture industry to meet growing protein demand. It considers two approaches: open-ocean net pen salmon farming or land-based recirculating aquaculture systems (RAS) for tilapia. From an environmental perspective, what is the main advantage of the RAS system?": "",
  "RAS systems contain waste and prevent disease transmission to wild populations, minimizing environmental impacts on marine ecosystems": "",
  "RAS systems produce more salmon than open-ocean farms": "",
  "RAS systems require no water or energy to operate": "",
  "Open-ocean farms have zero environmental impact": "",
  "Land-based RAS systems filter and recirculate water, containing waste products for proper treatment and eliminating the risk of disease and parasite transmission to wild fish populations; they also prevent escapees from interbreeding with wild stocks and avoid habitat impacts.": ""
}